Explanation:
We iterate through the string twice using nested loops. The outer loop iterates through the string once, and the inner loop iterates through the remaining characters after the outer loop. We keep track of the count and the maximum length found so far. If we find a substring with a higher count, we update the maximum length. This solution has a time complexity of O(n^2) because of the nested loops, where n is the length of the string. The space complexity is O(n) due to the use of the count and maxLength variables. The energy implications are low because the solution only requires a few arithmetic operations and comparisons.

